## ARCHITECTURE — ATOMIC DESIGN

Components are organized into 4 levels:
- **Atoms** — smallest building blocks (Button, Typography, Icon, Input, Badge, etc.)
- **Molecules** — composed from atoms (MenuItem, Menu, ButtonIcon, Breadcrumb, InputText, PageTitle, etc.)
- **Organisms** — complex sections (PageHeader, RotationGraph)
- **Templates** — pure UI main content of page layouts, NO logic, NO Redux, NO routing

To accommodate the best practice of Next.js routing, place files in the `app` folder under the designated folder.

Route group: `app/(public)/` — the public-facing pages. Files under this group:
- **`layout.tsx`** — `PublicLayout`: a `'use client'` layout that renders `PageHeader` at the top of every public page. It owns `NAV_ITEMS`, derives the active tab from `usePathname`, and navigates via `router.push`. It hides the search input on the landing page (`/`).
- **Page files** — HOC layer, ALL logic lives here (Redux hooks, `useRouter`, event handlers, data loading, etc.). The file name follows the URI.

Root layout: `app/layout.tsx` — wraps everything in `<ReduxProvider>` and `<ThemeProvider>`.

**Rule:** If you're writing `useState`, `useEffect`, `useRouter`, or `useAppSelector` — you're in a Page. If you're writing JSX — you're in a Template.

To make testing easy:
- "Template" from atomic design = UI main content
- "Page" from atomic design = connects HOC with the template

